"5. Moderately likely\n\nThe passage describes Bond's plan to take down Le Chiffre and his two gunmen by causing them to lose a considerable amount of money gambling. He successfully executes this plan by using a backward kick to knock the thin man's shins and causing him to whistle in pain, which in turn leads him to throw himself down the passage after Vesper. Bond then uses his fountain pen to shoot out his left hand, catching Bond's shoe at the top of its arc and twisting it sharply, causing minimal damage to Bond's hip.\n\nLe Chiffre then demands that Bond search him, and the two gunmen drag Bond to his feet. The Corsican then roughly strips Bond's revolver out of its shoulder holster and twists it around to search for other weaponry. Le Chiffre's attention is drawn to Bond's thoughts and he crosses the room to speak to him, suggesting that they not waste time.\n\nOverall, the passage is suspenseful as it builds up the tension and anticipation leading up to Bond's plan to take down Le Chiffre and the two gunmen. The use of descriptive language, such as \"spidery summons,\" \"fountain pen,\" and \"sharp twists,\" creates a sense of danger and intrigue"